For the parts, materials, and processes standardization and control program, interface definition shall include those management procedures which will enable the contractor's NH&S organizational element to:
(1) Review and concur with hardness parameters and parameter values in specifications;
(2) Review and concur with the methods of control and audit of hardness critical manufacturing processes and controls;
(3) Review and concur with all Class I and Class II engineering changes affecting parts, materials, and processes and to review and concur with the decision to use a Class I or Class II process;
(4) Review and concur with hardness critical item (HCI) failure analysis;
(5) Serve as the ultimate authority within the contractor's organization relative to HCI designation and identification and hardness design feature selection and implementation with appropriate checks and balances to allow for cost and schedule considerations after appropriate management review to allow the best decision in the government's interest to be made; and
(6) Provide direct support to studies of the effects of operating life on HCIs.
Other NH&S program interfaces (if such functions exist within the contract scope) described shall include:
(1) Design engineering;
(2) Systems engineering;
(3) Parts control board;
(4) Configuration management;
(5) Reliability program;
(6) Maintainability program;
(7) Quality assurance program;
(8) Logistics engineering;
(9) Aging and surveillance program;
(10) Worst case design analysis;
(11) System/cost effectiveness analysis;
(12) System acquisition life-cycle cost analysis;
(13) Assembly and checkout;
(14) Logistics support analysis;
(15) Operational test and evaluation program;
(16) Technical Order HCI content, especially annotation for HCPs
